{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:19:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21276"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21276"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.26,0.55,0.02,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43954"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a health check for insurance purposes. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a lifeguard at the local beach. Her family history of cancer includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFather diagnosed with bowel cancer at age 58\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaternal uncle had bladder cancer at age 55\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMother had ovarian cancer at age 42\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaternal cousin diagnosed with breast cancer at age 52\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the consultation, you discuss cancer screening options. Her cervical screening is up to date. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate screening plan to commence immediately?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Two-yearly urine cytology","Two-yearly mammography","Five-yearly colonoscopy","Three-monthly skin checks","Two-yearly pelvic ultrasound and CA-125 testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScreening recommendations are based on the lifetime risk of specific cancers and should be determined by the number and type of relatives affected as well as their age of diagnosis. This patient has a family history of several different cancers, but not all warrant specific screening protocols.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor colorectal cancer (CRC), there are three levels of risk stratification which have been developed by the NHMRC to guide screening. According to the RACGP Red Book guidelines, this patient belongs to category 2 (moderately increased risk) because she has one 1st-degree relative diagnosed with bowel cancer before the age of 60. Based on this, \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-yearly colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E starting now is appropriate. This is because screening should start 10 years before the earliest diagnosis in a first-degree relative (58 - 10 = 48) or at age 50, whichever comes first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo-yearly urine cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended based on a family history of bladder cancer in a second-degree relative (maternal uncle). There are no evidence-based screening recommendations for bladder cancer in asymptomatic individuals, even with a family history. Urine cytology has limited sensitivity for detecting early bladder cancer and would not be justified as a screening test in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo-yearly mammography\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated based on the family history provided. According to the RACGP guidelines, the patient has a third-degree relative (maternal cousin) with breast cancer at age 52, which does not significantly increase her risk to warrant early or more frequent screening than the general population. The RACGP recommends mammography screening every two years for women aged 50-74 years in the general population. A family history of breast cancer in a third-degree relative does not meet criteria for high-risk screening protocols.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree-monthly skin checks\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate recommendation. While the patient works as a lifeguard, representing occupational sun exposure, there is no evidence to support a recommendation for such frequent skin examinations at this presentation. The RACGP guidelines recommend skin self-examination and appropriate sun protection measures for those at increased risk of skin cancer, with clinical skin examinations at a frequency determined by individual risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo-yearly pelvic ultrasound and CA-125 testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for ovarian cancer screening, even with a family history of ovarian cancer in a first-degree relative (mother). The RACGP guidelines explicitly state that population screening for ovarian cancer is not currently recommended as there is insufficient evidence that it reduces mortality, and both ultrasound and CA-125 have high false-positive rates leading to unnecessary interventions. Specific ovarian cancer screening would only be considered in the context of known genetic mutations (e.g., BRCA1/2) or in families with multiple affected first-degree relatives with ovarian or breast cancer suggesting a hereditary cancer syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the most appropriate screening plan is five-yearly colonoscopy starting now at age 48, based on the moderate risk of colorectal cancer due to her father\u0027s diagnosis at age 58. For the ovarian cancer risk, genetic counseling might be considered to assess for hereditary cancer syndromes, but routine screening with ultrasound and CA-125 is not recommended according to RACGP guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colonoscopy starting 10 years before the diagnosis of 1st-degree relative is recommended for patients at moderate risk (category two) of colorectal cancer.","Colorectal cancer risk stratification takes into account the number of 1st- and 2nd-degree relatives affected and their age of diagnosis.","Family history of ovarian cancer in a first-degree relative without known genetic mutations does not warrant specific screening protocols outside of general population recommendations."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Guidelines for preventive activities in general practice (\u2018Red\u202fBook\u2019), 10th edn. East\u202fMelbourne, Vic: RACGP; 2024 Jun 28 [updated 2024 Sep 24]. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/about-the-red-book","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Guidelines for preventive activities in general practice \u2013 Colorectal cancer. In: Guidelines for preventive activities in general practice (\u2018Red\u202fBook\u2019), 10th edn. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP; 2024 Sep 24 [updated 2024 Sep 24]. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21276"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T14:35:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T14:36:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14149"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":